title: For Sale/Trade:  Lee Enfield No. 1 Mk III
location: Rocky Mount, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Lee Enfield No. 1 MKIII ishapore scrub. All matching numbers besides the magizine. Century Arms Import. Has a FR 44 which stands for field repair 1944 on the left side of the receiver. If you know about scrubs they were early British made rifles used by the Brits in India than later sold to the Indian Forces. After the war and the British lost power in India, the India Army scrubbed the British Markings from the receiver and barrels and put a screw in the stock to match the no.1 MKIII they were producing. 

This rifle has the screw, but it serves no purpose unlike the Indian rifles. All matching numbers besides the magazine. The serial number is pretty low for a mass produced war rifle. Metal is in good shape, besides minor pitting on the left side of receiver. This rifle still has one Brit marking on the barrel. The bore has strong rifling. This rifle is a great shooter. The stock was refinished, and it is more glossy than satin. Has the Indian marks on the stock. 

Cash Price is $200 or best offer.  I will not ship. Face to face transaction only. Thanks for your interest.

title: For Sale/Trade:  U.S. Model of 1917 (Winchester)
postcontent:
This should hold interest for someone looking to pick up a piece of history, a hunter looking for a good, but inexpensive, .30-06, or a collector looking to restore a coveted 1917 Winchester matched barrel/receiver.

I'm looking to sell a U.S. Model of 1917 Winchester Serial No. 447293. I would describe the rifle as service grade, fully functioning, shoots more accurately that I was expecting (more accurately that I do), minor pitting in the barrel, all parts present except that the stock was "sporterized" in that the front (muzzle end) ~10 inches of wood was cut off, sanded down and refinished. I know that for the collector it will take a hit for whomever chopped the stock and for having some mismatched parts. I have test fired this gun and it definitely works and definitely hits what you're aiming at.

I am asking $350, preferably FTF in Northern Virginia.
I would accept trades of a Glock 19 (maybe a Glock 23, 3.8 XDM or M&P compact of any caliber) and would be more than willing to add cash to complete the trade.

For the hunter, I've attached pictures, for the potential collector, here is the run down of the markings from the muzzle to the butt:

The front sight has had the ears cut off but is marked "W"

Just behind the front sight, there is a "W," then a flaming bomb, then "9-18"

Front sling attachment is marked "W"

The side of the barrel, just before the chamber is marked "RU322"

Top of barrel (at the chamber) is marked with a flaming bomb, three eagle's heads (both faded) under one there appears to be "P-3?" under another "?-?0" and under the third "P-3?"

There may be a "20 on the barrel but one of the eagle heads overlaps making it difficult to see.

There is a flaming bomb and two eagle heads on the receiver, under one of them is "p.30" and under the other is what looks like "J-6"

The rear sight is marked "W"

The bolt, firing pin and cocking piece are all marked with "E" and the cocking piece also has a flaming bomb and what looks like a "U".

The stock is marked "6E" in one spot, "S" in another, and has a couple of eagle heads with what looks like "600" under one.

The buttplate is marked "W"

Those were the markings I found in a surface survey, if I need to break the rifle down further I can.
